<div class="xar-mod-page">
    <div class="xar-mod-head">
        <xar:if condition="!xarRequestIsAJAX()">
            <xar:template type="module" module="base" file="admin-menu" />
        </xar:if>
    </div>
    <div class="xar-mod-body">
        <h1><xar:mlstring>Overview</xar:mlstring></h1>
        <div class="xar-mod-content">
            <img src="#xarTplGetImage('admin.png', 'modules')#" alt="official icon" width="96" height="96" class="xar-module-icon" />
            <h2><xar:mlstring>What is it?</xar:mlstring></h2>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>The Modules Module determines which modules are available on your Xarigami installation
                by controlling the install, upgrade, and removal of modules. The Modules Module also provides options
                to add further functionality in these modules through management of module hook configurations.
                </xar:mlstring>
            </p>

            <h3><xar:mlstring>How to use it?</xar:mlstring></h3>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>From the menu, you have two choices:</xar:mlstring>
            </p>

            <ul>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring><strong>View All</strong>: Allows you to see what modules are currently installed on
                    your system, and the current state that they are in.</xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring><strong>Configure Hooks</strong>: Allows you to add extra functionality to modules by
                    configuring hooks from one module to another. For example, setting a hook to display comments
                    (the Comments module) in articles (Articles module).</xar:mlstring>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <xar:mlstring><strong>Modify Config</strong>: Change configuration options related to the Modules module, or modules in general.</xar:mlstring>
                </li>

            </ul>

        <a name="list" title="list"><h4><xar:mlstring>View All</xar:mlstring></h4></a>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>The View All option at default setup displays a list of all modules that are available,
                but not necessarily active and installed in your Xarigami installation. All valid Xarigami modules found
                in your Xarigami modules directory should be listed here.</xar:mlstring>
            </p>
            <ol>
                <li><xar:mlstring>You can add more modules to this list at any time by adding them to your Xarigami
                  modules directory and clicking the Reload button</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>Modules must be installed and active to be available for use on your Xarigami site.
                You may also need to setup the appropriate privileges for your users to view or use the module
                (See Privileges module and Roles module).</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>You must check to ensure any modules in upgrade status are upgraded and set to
                active in order to use them</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>You cannot uninstall or deactivate core modules</xar:mlstring></li>
            </ol>
            <p><xar:mlstring>There are a number of options with drop down selection lists that you should check
            when displaying your modules.</xar:mlstring></p>
            <ol>
               <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Style</strong>: Configures the interface style for display of modules.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><strong>View</strong>: Changes the current modules view. By default ALL modules are displayed.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Sort By</strong>: This is the sort order for the module list.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><strong>Hide</strong>: Check this to hide core modules.</xar:mlstring></li>
           </ol>

            <p><xar:mlstring>Within the view itself we have the following headers.</xar:mlstring></p>
            <ol>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Name</em>: The module name.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Version</em>: The module version number.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Info</em>: Some basic module information.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Status</em>: The current status of the module.</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Actions</em>: Displays the actions available to you for this module</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Properties</em>: Provides a link that allows you to alter the module display
               in the User or Admin menu</xar:mlstring></li>
               <li><xar:mlstring><em>Hooks</em>: This provides an alternative means for setting hooks from other modules
               to on or off. If you do not understand this setting, please use the 'Configuring Hooks' settings below
               to configure and set functionality with hooks.</xar:mlstring></li>
            </ol><br />

        <h4><xar:mlstring>Configure Hooks</xar:mlstring></h4>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>This menu link displays the Module Hooks Configuration page. Each of the installed and
                 active modules here can provide additional functionality in other modules through the use of 'hooks'.
                 </xar:mlstring>
            </p>
            <blockquote>
            <p><xar:mlstring><strong>Important</strong></xar:mlstring>:</p>
            <p><xar:mlstring>To use the hook functionality  provided by a module, click on the module that provides the hook, and
            then check the checkbox next to the module where you want to add that hook functionality.</xar:mlstring></p>
            </blockquote>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>As an example, if you wish to provide comments in articles, you need to activate the
                comments hook provided by the  Comments module and allow that for the articles module. Comments
                module provides the hook so click on Comments, then check the checkbox next to the Article module,
                or one of the Articles module itemtypes to display the output of the comments hook in that module
                or itemtype.</xar:mlstring>
            </p>
            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>Taking the Comments module as an example, if you click on Comments and then browse
                the list you'll see you have the following options for each module where you may wish to hook and
                activate Comments:</xar:mlstring>
            </p><br />

            <ul style="margin-left:20px;">
                <li><xar:mlstring>Do NOT enable Comments functionality in [module name]</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>Enable the Comments hooks for ALL items in [module name]</xar:mlstring></li>
                <li><xar:mlstring>Enable Comments functionality for SOME itemtypes in [module name]</xar:mlstring></li>
            </ul>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>The last option allows you to activate the hook and display Comments in say News or
                 Reviews, but not Documents for example.</xar:mlstring>
            </p>
        <br />

            <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Blocks</xar:mlstring></h3>

            <p>
                <xar:mlstring>The Modules Module has no blocks included at this time.</xar:mlstring>
            </p>

            <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Hooks</xar:mlstring></h3>

            <p><xar:mlstring>The Modules Module has no hooks included at this time.</xar:mlstring></p>
            <h3><xar:mlstring>Included Dynamic Data Properties</xar:mlstring></h3>

            <p><xar:mlstring>For developers, the Dynamic Module property is included and provides a drop down selection list of available Modules.</xar:mlstring></p>

           <h3><xar:mlstring>Further Information</xar:mlstring></h3>
           <p>
              <xar:mlstring>Further information on the Modules module can be found at</xar:mlstring>
           </p>
           <ul>
               <li><xar:mlstring>Related tutorials and documentation on Modules module found at</xar:mlstring> <a href="http://xarigami.com/project/xarigami_core/" title="#xarML('Related documentation on Modules')#"><xar:mlstring>Xarigami Documentation.</xar:mlstring></a>
              </li>
          </ul>
